1. Project Posting Framework
Here's a reusable template with guidance notes for each field.

Card-level fields (listing grid)
FieldGuidanceExampleTitleShort, descriptive project name (3–5 words). Can be the preserve/client + topic, or the method + system.Coastal Wildlife AssessmentSubtitleOne phrase that clarifies scope or novelty — the "what makes this interesting" hook.Biodiversity baseline for a new preserveDescription1–2 sentences. Lead with the deliverable, then the ecological question or management need it addressed.Interactive technical report evaluating camera performance and establishing a mammal biodiversity baseline.Tags3–6 tags (see tag list below). Include at least one method tag, one topic tag, and one deliverable tag.camera trap · occupancy · technical reportImageSquare crop. Prefer a figure, map, or graphic from the project over a generic wildlife photo.—

Page-level sections (project detail page)
Project overview (2–4 sentences)
Who was the client, what was the system, and what was the core question or need? This sets context before getting into methods.
Objectives (bulleted list, 3–5 items)
What specific questions or tasks did the project address? These should map to the deliverables.
Approach (short paragraph)
Methods and tools used. Mention data types, analytical frameworks, and any noteworthy technical choices (e.g., reproducible pipeline, multi-state model, collaborative design process).
Key findings or deliverables (bulleted list or short paragraph)
What were the results, outputs, or recommendations? Be specific enough to be credible; avoid over-summarizing.
Links (as applicable)

🔗 Interactive report
📄 PDF download
📁 Public repository
📑 Publication

Citation
Full citation in consistent format.

2. Tag List
Organized into categories to make selection easier. Each project should use one or more tags from each relevant category.
Analysis method
camera trap · occupancy model · species richness · population trend · study design · data synthesis · spatial analysis · connectivity · statistical consulting · reproducible workflow · data visualization

Note on camera trap: Yes, give it its own tag — it's your highest-demand service area and appears in most projects. Use it as the primary method tag for any camera-based work, then add a second method tag (e.g., occupancy model, species richness) to distinguish the analytical approach.

Topic / domain
mammal monitoring · invasive species · fire ecology · prescribed grazing · plant diversity · biodiversity baseline · habitat use · landscape connectivity · climate resilience · conservation planning
Deliverable type
technical report · presentation · interactive report · peer-reviewed · data pipeline · field protocol · map